They are both labelled pass-by-value because they are both pass-by-value.  Yes, they are different, but that doesn&#x27;t mean one is pass-by-reference and the other is pass-by-value.<p>The C example is equivalent to<p><pre><code>  pa = &a;
  pb = &b;
  swap(pa, pb);
</code></pre>
When <i>swap</i> returns, the values of <i>pa</i> and <i>pb</i> are unchanged.  Only the values or <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> are changed.  But <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> were not passed to swap.  Therefore this is not pass-by-reference, but rather passing a pointer to a variable by value.
